 relationships, node status (N0 vs. N1) intricately dictates treatment, with node-negative patients often favoring surgery or SABR, while node-positive cases may trend towards systemic therapy first. The relationships show that even within operable groups, node status modulates the preferred interventions, thereby customizing each patient's path [Data: Entities (208, 32, 270, 271); Relationships (488, 86, 90, 665)].\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"rating\": 8.5,\n  \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high because this community represents the structure of NSCLC clinical decision-making protocols, directly influencing patient outcomes and institutional compliance across cancer care settings.\"\n}", "refusal": null, "role": "assistant", "annotations": [], "audio": null, "function_call": null, "tool_calls": null, "provider_specific_fields": {"refusal": null}}, "provider_specific_fields": {}}], "created": 1784869008, "model": "gpt-4.1-2025-04-14", "object": "chat.completion", "moderation": null, "service_tier": "default", "system_fingerprint": "fp_59cee91353", "usage": {"completion_tokens": 1341, "prompt_tokens": 3011, "total_tokens": 4352, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": 0, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 0, "rejected_prediction_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cache_write_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 1408}}, "formatted_response": null, "content": "{\n  \"title\": \"Operability and Treatment Pathways in Node-Negative and Node-Positive NSCLC\",\n  \"summary\": \"This community encompasses entities and relationships central to the decision pathways and interventions for patients with non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC), focusing on operability assessments, surgical findings, and node status-based protocols. Core entities include the determination of operability, operative interventions (including neoadjuvant therapy and surgical resection), staging details (such as T/N status), and specific protocol s